liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The ASX futures are pointing to a modest 0.3% rise when the local market opens, a long way off the S & P 500's 1.6% jump on Friday. That, in turn, was left behind by the Nasdaq's 2.1% surge, the biggest one-day rise since May, according to NAB analysts, as tech giants bounded ahead. " Microsoft and Nvidia stole some of the headlines with the former climbing above $US369 (a new record high, +2.49% on the day) while the latter extended its recent gains to an eighth consecutive day," noted NAB's senior FX strategist Rodrigo Catril. "Looking at equities' performance over the past week, tech stocks have been the big winners with the NASDAQ up an impressive 7.89% with Japan's Nikkei outscoring the S & P 500, up 6.1% vs 5.96% for the latter. "Meanwhile Chinese equities remain in struggle street with the CSI 300 0.08% on the week while the Hang Seng was -1.17%." That shows where, on average, Australia's economic bread is buttered, with a struggling Chinese economy dragging on both Australian equities and the currency. The Australian dollar is worth 63.45 US cents.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Big tech led US market surge, ASX poised to lag well behind

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: ANZ's full-year results are out, with the key statutory profit after tax flat at $7.1 billion. The bank's preferred measure of cash profit from continuing operations jumped 14 per cent to $7.4 billion. ANZ is paying a final dividend of 94 cents per share, 81 cents of which will be partially franked at 65 per cent with 13 cents unfranked. "This is a strong annual result, with record revenue and cash profit following several years of transformation, enabling us to continue to support our customers and improve their banking experience," the bank's chief executive Shayne Elliott said. "We continued to strengthen our balance sheet and closed the year with provisions for potential credit losses higher than prior to the pandemic, and with more capital than ever before. This is critical as we enter a period of continued high interest rates, rising costs and geopolitical tensions." We'll have more details, analysis and market reaction to the ANZ result throughout the morning.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: ANZ posts $7.1 billion profit, 14 per cent cash earnings boost
